    "body": "This is one example of a message that causes this: \r\n```\r\nb'\\x01\\xf8{\\x05\\xa9odash/v1.0.0-stable/windows-amd64/go1.8.3\\xcc\\xc5\\x83eth?\\xc5\\x83eth>\\x80\\xb8@.\\x1bb\\x00s>\\xb77W\\xb6\\x1bhK{V\\x865\\x8b\\x0e\\x15\\x86\\x90\\xeb)\\x90-\\xee\\xd0]\\x95<\\xac\\xe2 \\xc4\\xf9\\xf3\\x01\\xb4\\x8a\\xee\\xdc\\xea\\x90b\\xc4\\t\\xc9d\\x18S$\\xbb\\xc9\\xa1gI\\x1clY\\xe0\\x94\\xc4\\xf9'\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe first byte is the command id. In this case it is 0x01, which is the `Disconnect` command, but the payload (see below) matches exactly that of the `Hello` command (see https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/%C3%90%CE%9EVp2p-Wire-Protocol), which suggests a broken client implementation.\r\n\r\n```\r\n>>> rlp.decode(d[1:])\r\n[b'\\x05', b'odash/v1.0.0-stable/windows-amd64/go1.8.3', [[b'eth', b'?'], [b'eth', b'>']], b'', b'.\\x1bb\\x00s>\\xb77W\\xb6\\x1bhK{V\\x865\\x8b\\x0e\\x15\\x86\\x90\\xeb)\\x90-\\xee\\xd0]\\x95<\\xac\\xe2 \\xc4\\xf9\\xf3\\x01\\xb4\\x8a\\xee\\xdc\\xea\\x90b\\xc4\\t\\xc9d\\x18S$\\xbb\\xc9\\xa1gI\\x1clY\\xe0\\x94\\xc4\\xf9']\r\n```\r\n\r\nLooks like that's coming from a casper client (https://github.com/ethereum/pyethapp/issues/288), although I can't seem to find the code for it\r\n\r\nI think the best alternative here is to catch that exception in `Disconnect.decode()` and log a warning",
